  <description type="3">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Smallholder Farmers</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Smallholder farmers make up 90% of farming in Uganda, but most of these farmers produce as individuals at the subsistence level with limited surpluses to sell and fail to engage in any meaningful agribusiness due to lack of access to lucrative markets. The marketing problems include inadequacy of funds, limited value addition, poor flow of market information, weak bargaining power, and weak institutions. The quality of their produce/products is generally low, a factor which hinders access to markets and gives them low bargaining power. Thus the farmers do not benefit fully from farming, which is their major economic activity.
Objectives
The goal of this project is to improve the livelihoods of smallholder farmers in Uganda through sustainable agriculture. The strategic objective is that targeted smallholder bean, coffee, and maize farmers of the greater Masaka area increase their incomes from the marketing of their cash crops. This will be achieved through the following outcomes:
Objective #1 Targeted farmers practice farming as a business.
Objective #2 Targeted framers operate viable farm businesses.</narrative>
  </description>
